commentBody:
@Jeff 

Nope.

I’ve dabbled here enough to know Barry Ancona is a class act. Gracious. Fair. Font of puzzle knowledge.

@NYC Traveler

Similar experience.  Slow to build on the gimmes.  Choices like showER and zooMED took a while to clean up.  Finished close to my Friday average.

Last entry in the NE, largely due to thinking that the lavatory answer had to be a misdirection.  O tempora, o mores.

@Marshall Walthew

Very similar solving experience.

But, instead of BEOWULF, I was pleased by the clue for ETNA, since my family has always claimed to be descended from Hephaestus.

@Tompi 

Thank you! I was actually just being silly. See, I like to think I'm funny. At least I amuse myself, anyhow!  Ha! 😏 

But I do appreciate your kind answer!  ☺️

@JLG

Nicely put. 

Hard crosswords are out there. The Newsday Saturday Stumper. Peter Gordon’s Fireball. Tim Croce’s Club 72. And probably others I can’t think of.

@JLG - I agree 100%. 

Although I am sad that so many of the late-week puzzles have become so easy over the past year or so, I will continue to support the NYT.

Given that the most powerful government in the world is now clearly trying to destroy legitimate journalism, I have concluded this: even if I decided that the games were no longer worth the cost of the subscription, I would still continue to subscribe, just to continue my support of journalism.

@Times Rita

You do have to pay $20/yr for xwordinfo.com, but it's worth it, in my opinion.

(Certain features, like the daily solution, are available to everyone.)

@DQ

Yes I think this was as easy as a sub-average Monday.  Absolutely.  I would not be so shocked and worked up otherwise.  There was nothing to it.  And apparently 97% of players agree.

It's a bad sign and a bad trend.  There is less and less reason to pay for this.  Meanwhile the free LA Times somehow remains frequently challenging.  The NYT is giving away its gaming reputation with both hands.  Destroying the very thing that made it attractive enough to fund the paper's livelihood.  It's bizarre.

@HeathieJ

Ye gods! Really?

🙃

@B

TIL that "dumbening" is a word, so thanks.

But I really shouldn't be TIL'ing more new words from the comments than I am from the puzzles lately, should I?

@DQ
But why are they catering ONLY to the people who want an easier puzzle?

Where are the puzzles for those of us who want a challenge?

@DQ

Interesting new strain of populist commentary I’m suddenly seeing crop up — crosswords for the people!

I mean, I guess I can appreciate the honesty (as opposed to debating the premise, i.e. gaslighting), but I just don’t get the mentality. The NYT crossword became the brand/institution it is in large part because of its reputation for tricky Thursdays and hard Saturdays, and those challenges have been a huge draw for many longtime subscribers. Why does *every* day of the week have to be beginner friendly?

@DQ

How long have you been solving?

What happens when, in five or ten more years, you yourself have progressed to the point where there's no challenge to even a Saturday puzzle?

@B

I thought you had, too.

But turns out you didn't.

@Whoa Nellie From the point of view of pure UX, the optimum is a mix of high difficulty and low difficulty puzzles. (Dopamine (q.v.).)

Thus someone like me, averaging 40 mins for a Saturday, is excited to knock one over in 13.

If there’s a clever plan in place it’s probably that, though I suspect it’s just natural variation around a difficulty mean that’s slowly decreasing over time. (Saturdays from 2016 are genuinely much harder — there are months where I average well over an hour after eventually conceding things will have to be looked up.)

@Whoa Nellie

@Lewis was indeed spot on earlier this week, but your synopsis here:

Today's grid had me wondering if I was a crossword solver, or an unwilling participant in Wheel of Fortune.

is the truth burn of the month.

@George
12:51 for me. It usually takes me around 45:00.

I am not amused.

@Becky

In case you don't know, here are some vintage acrostics. I did a bunch of them lately but needed a lot of help. But came up with a new bibliography.

<a href="https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/premium/xword/acrostic/acrostic.html" target="_blank">https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/premium/xword/acrostic/acrostic.html</a>

@Becky

The second Sunday puzzles are available to solve at xwordinfo.com.  You do have to pay their annual $20 subscription, but it's well worth it.  As mentioned in another thread, you can also solve pre-Shortz archived puzzles.

I just renewed my subscription the other day.

@Anita & @The X-Phile
(sounds like a good name for a band)

Dainty doesn't have negative connotations for me, and TWEE definitely does--not that it's a word I ever use, but I do know it when I hear it. Definitions and synonyms online are all over the place, but for me the good ones say it means excessively or affectedly dainty, delicate, cute, sentimental, or quaint.

@MrB
Consider yourself fortunate that both my earlier replies were deleted. I hope you were able to enjoy them while they lasted.

Could it be your alleged lack of affordability of a phone could be mitigated by using your subscription dollars more wisely?

@Helen Wright
DITTO. I had ORCS for a shamefully long time till I remembered who was on which side. My LOTR cred is in jeopardy.

Side note: autocomplete wanted "shamelessly" there until I got to the F, and  took a couple MORE letters after that to catch on. Does this say something about our times?

@Paul
I confidently entered orcS.
I too hang my head in shame.

@Times Rita

I agree with almost everything you said, but I don't like using the "d" word.  Ever, really, and definitely not here.  This is all about experience.  I'm not any smarter today than I was when I struggled (and failed) to solve.  It's really all about learning what tricks might be played, how to interpret clues, how to be a better guesser, and having the perseverance needed to improve.

Maybe people are less patient now, and have an expectation that they should be able to succeed right away.  Maybe the rush to come here to make a comment makes the idea of putting the puzzle away for an hour, or a day (or more) unthinkable.

@Nancy J.
I mean, isn't the Midi supposed to be easier? Why can't the Midi be the easy puzzle, and this the hard one?

I honestly can't justify spending so much money on something I'm not enjoying. I've been cutting subscriptions lately, and this one might be next on my list.

@Puzzlemucker

Nice to see you here. 

Nice comment. I especially like your evocation of the sad state of affairs at the WaPo without mentioning it by name. (I have no such sense of restraint.)

@Puzzlemucker
@Eric Hougland

I also like the evocation of the guy who's name rhymes with Gεff Hεzos.

It's just horrifying, what billionaires are doing to this country.

@Francis
I hate to stomp on the grave but your nation has voted again and again for unbridled capitalism and against labour rights, redistributive taxes, and the tiniest effort to build a social system that protects the commons and assists the weak. 
What did you all expect?

@Paul Turner

"Things that are tough on the outside and doughy on the inside?"

Not quite.

@Kat

Thanks. 

I live in the US but had no idea either.

@Anya

It’s awesome how international our readers picks are today. Like 5 out of top 6. 

And it’s certainly not lost on anyone that someone from Ukraine noted a group that was ‘assimilated’ by Russia. Wonder how the editors feel about that one. In all seriousness

@Lewis
@Barry Ancona

Barry's right--I, too, want to hear from bizzaro Lewis as well.

@Mu

Or one can learn on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday puzzles as was done in the past.  When I started solving, I knew the late week puzzles were beyond my level, but with time, I gained the skills needed to solve them.

Solving wise, what do you have to look forward to if you can do the end of week puzzles in year one?

@Mu
This was more than "a hint or two." The entire puzzle was clued at a Tuesday level.

The whole point of having a progression of difficulty is so that people of ALL skill levels can enjoy themselves. As it is now, there is nothing for high-level solvers to look forward to. There is no challenge anymore.

@Merry

I've experienced no such issues.  Nor have I experienced any of the "Midi disappearing" issues some have spoken of.

And B, just because you turn the timer off, that doesn't mean it isn't running.  You just can't see it.

@Merry
The midi is still very glitchy, but I haven't noticed problems with the timer on it or the mini.

I *do* have serious issues with the timer on the main puzzle.

@B

I’m just at a loss as to why I’ve experienced none of the problems you and some other solvers have. And the reverse. 

(I do have some ridiculous times—including a couple of 0:00 solves—in the Archive, a long time ago.)

@Xword Junkie

Agreed, and well said. I also liked [Stuck under a blanket, perhaps]. But it was the SE that broke the puzzle open for me! I then worked my way back up to the NW. Solved while drinking my first cup of coffee of the day, so it definitely was a case of increasing clarity of mind as I worked through it.

Personal childhood memories with the LORAX, and my dad jokingly telling us "Put up your dukes!" while play-shadow boxing. That warm feeling is worth the price of admission for me!

@Weak

It suckers me in too sometimes, thinking wow maybe I've gotten really good at these.  That's why I've taken to doing reality checks against the comments and XWStats.  Very nearly always, if I found it simple everyone else did too.

That wasn't really necessary today.  This was a farce of a Saturday.

@Linda Jo
I had orcs too, but my daughter was snuggled up with me and she corrected me. 

I still struggled with that upper right

@momonjava

I've only just started doing Friday and Saturday in the last few months. 

How far back do you recommend going for a more challenging Saturday?

@MamaIshtari

I've been (very slowly) working my way backwards in the archives. I'm currently in mid-2021, and those Saturday puzzles can be plenty hard! 

(Fwiw, I started solving regularly three or four years ago, and first went through the archives doing M-W only, but only back a few years.)

@inky

You need to be a subscriber to access those puzzles.  It costs $20/yr and allows access to all of the site, including pre-Shortz solving archives and various searching tools.

I find that the subscription cost is well worth it.

@Barry Ancona
Which is, what?
C'mon, get to the point!

@Lpr

It is obvious that experienced solvers get better with time, but that doesn’t account for the recent—past year or two—near-universal agreement of experienced solvers, and data from xwstats.com, that says that the puzzle is getting easier. 

This wave of comments, along with supporting data, has never been seen before.

@MaryEllen

If you (in the general sense) are relatively new and haven’t been around long to notice the decline in difficulty, it’s certainly understandable that you might disbelieve these comments. But I think few if any experienced solvers are deliberately trolling newer solvers, unless they are putting forth know-it-all opinions in comments that include hints that they’re not experienced enough to have seen the change. 

Some of these telltale signs include accusing longtime solvers of bragging because they say the puzzles are easier, calling constructors “creators” or similar things, and not getting the entirety of a theme but calling the puzzle bad anyway.

@MaryEllen
It would be nice to know what you found clunky and poor. I found the fill extremely fresh, and even the bits of glue (SEERS, ENTS, ETNA) were mostly well-clued.
I didn't even see much poor clueing, although a lot of it was nowhere near Saturday difficulty.

@Brian

There are people who have been solving the NYT crossword for 40 plus years.  There are others who've been solving for 25 years.  I've been solving for 10 years. 

If our perception that the puzzle is getting easier is due to experience, why are we all finding that the puzzles have changed dramaticlly in the past several years?  Shouldn't the 40 year solvers have hit that point 30 years ago?  Shouldn't the 30 year solvers have hit that point 20 years ago?  Why would we all arrive at the same timeline for when the puzzles became markedly easier?

@McT

This is not a bug. It a new feature put in place to convince solvers that the puzzles have not gotten easier: "Look, that one took you more than three hours!"

[Seriously---send email to <a href="mailto:nytgames@nytimes.com">nytgames@nytimes.com</a>]

@B

Took me longer than today's NYT, but not as long as the ones from ten years ago that I mentioned in an earlier thread.

Well, actually, just about the same time as one of them.

@B et al,

I found this puzzle pretty crunchy, as well. The grid design made it harder to get a toehold, what with the grid being split up into three different sections. Some of the references were pretty hard, but a lot came surprisingly easy to me. All told, it only took me a few minutes longer than today’s NYT puzzle. 

JUSTTOBECLEAR, today’s was well under my average. My earlier comment from last night that it was a “Saturday puzzle” was only to point out that I had to give some serious thought to a lot of the clues, and was not a reflection of my solving time. It was a nice change to have a challenge. My apologies for any confusion.

@bayonetta 

there's always some spoilsport finding a silver lining

😎

@Hugh, I'm slowly coming around to that point of view! So much criticism, and much of it borders on rude. 

Too hard, too easy, offense found where none exists. . . Obviously neither the editors nor the  constructors can please everyone but it feels like things have gone off the rails.

Generally speaking, I love my daily immersion in word nerd territory. Sometimes it's not exactly my cup of tea, and I do it and move on without feeling the need to castigate anyone for my lack of enjoyment. The fact that I don't like/enjoy a particular puzzle doesn't mean there is something wrong with it!

@Ginny
Hi Ginny,
My experience has been that most of the Saturday puzzles are at the easier level of the past 2-3 years.  However once in a while, maybe once every two months give or take, NYTCWP goes old school on us and puts out a killer-diller like the good old Satur-days.  You're liable to hit on one of those, and in my experience it is a feeling of stymied stultification, and for me at least, a multi-day endeavor.  Hey I ain't proud, except when I am.  X-D lolol

@JohnWM

Are you trying to line us?

/it's just peanuts

@Norwood

I gave it a try.  Couldn't even engage.

Too hard to read (size and color).  Can't enlarge.  Can't print.

@Barry Ancona

Yeah, it took me almost twice as long. And then I started on their version of the Bee and realized I haven't finished the Bee here. So that's less time on this platform than usual.

I did enjoy today's grid. Shortz' shepherding leads to the selection and polishing of puzzles with a certain clever humor that pulls me back again and again. It was really quick, but tasty. Going elsewhere to fill up.

@Ron

I've had three prostate biopsies, one of them to remote areas that made my urologist squirm as he was telling me about the sampling targets.

So more in agreement with your observation I could not be.

@Boaz Moser
thank you so much for stopping by. The puzzle really was lovely. Your cut clues for LOCKER and TIED are so much more Saturday.
Like others, I wish we had been given the opportunity to solve the puzzle your students solved.

@B Sorry that I wasn't clear: the students *did* solve the published version, and found it very difficult. Point is, even if the Saturday experience is shifting easier overall, there are still amateur solvers out there who have it! 

In my opinion the editors do make things easier, but it must be said part of that is related to making things *cleaner*. Many of my hard clues that get changed involve stretchy wordplay, convoluted phrasing, or niche references, if I'm being honest. Take the TIED clue I mentioned. I like it, but totally get why it was cut!

I also wouldn't say I'm "barely rewarded"— the fact that I get to make money off a dear hobby at all is amazing! Perhaps I wish NYT bumped up its payscale to keep pace with their raising standards and overall inflation, but hey, it's whatever.

@MaryEllen If you want to hear my two cents on this, I agree that "old" is not bad! Even outdated terms keep relevance as a reminder of a specific time or culture.

What I meant by "old" is the type of niche fill that was once common but no longer passes muster. Things like variant spellings, niche technical words, or acronyms that aren't inferrable anymore. Personally, I want every entry in my crosswords to be good on their own terms, not just good because decades-long solvers will be familiar with them by now.

YE GODS from this puzzle is a good example of "old" fill I like! Nobody really says it anymore, at least not that I've heard, but it's so evocative of a certain period. For me, I instantly picture a grizzled 19th century sea captain staring agape. "Put up your DUKES" is also old Cockney rhyming slang that I think is interesting!

@Boaz Moser
I loved this puzzle. I solved it pretty quickly (for me) but the clues and fill were fun and fresh. My favorite was ARMOREDCARS. 
More please!
